# simgit — Implementation Plan
# "A Borrow Checker for Filesystems"
# Simultaneous Git: Virtual Overlay for Multi-Agent Codebases
# ============================================================

## 1. Problem Statement

Modern multi-agent coding pipelines (e.g., 10–100 autonomous coding agents
working on the same repository) have no safe concurrency primitive at the
filesystem level. Git branches solve logical isolation, but they require disk
copies (worktrees), drift apart from HEAD quickly, and give agents no
awareness of what their siblings are doing. The result is:

  - Race conditions (two agents overwriting the same file)
  - Wasted disk space (N worktrees × repo size)
  - Context blindness (Agent A cannot see Agent B's in-flight changes)
  - Merge chaos (rebasing many diverged branches)

simgit solves this by implementing Rust-style ownership semantics
(shared-immutable reads, exclusive-mutable writes) at the VFS layer, making
conflict detection instantaneous rather than post-hoc.


## 2. Core Concepts

  PRIMARY VIEW
    A read-only projection of the current HEAD commit. Every agent sees this
    as the authoritative baseline. Zero additional disk space.

  AGENT SESSION
    A lightweight context bound to a Task ID. Carries a delta layer (the
    "mutable borrow"). Created in microseconds; consumes space only for the
    files that were actually written.

  DELTA LAYER (Copy-on-Write)
    When an agent writes file F, the VFS captures the new content in the
    agent's private delta store instead of touching the real file. Reads of
    F within that session transparently return the delta version. Reads by
    other agents still see the original.

  BORROW REGISTRY
    A kernel-side (or daemon-side) table: { path → (readers[], writer?) }.
    Enforces the invariant: at most one writer per path at any time.
    "Compile-time" (i.e., at open() time) errors surface to the agent
    before any mutation happens.

  FLATTEN / COMMIT
    When an agent session ends successfully, the daemon applies its delta
    layer to a new git branch in one atomic operation. No merge is needed
    unless two agents touched overlapping paths — in which case human or
    automated review is required.


